My name is Dr Jenna Wraith and I'm the head of the Sustainable Futures department at QCIF,

00:00:13.680 --> 00:00:18.160
which is a non-for-profit organisation with a focus on building digital infrastructure for

00:00:18.160 --> 00:00:24.000
researchers and I lead the EcoCommons project. Today I'm going to talk to you about how we make

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:28.320
modelling accessible and the barriers that we have faced along the way so you can hopefully

00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:34.560
address some of this in your own work. But before I dive in, it's customary in Australia

00:00:34.560 --> 00:00:39.200
to first acknowledge the traditional custodians on the land that we're meeting today. For me,

00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:44.080
it's the Wiradjuri people and I'd like to pay my respects to elders past, present and emerging

00:00:44.080 --> 00:00:48.799
and extend that respect to all traditional custodians on the lands that we're meeting today.

00:00:50.560 --> 00:00:55.279
So my role in the EcoCommons project started with something as ordinary as a USB stick.

00:00:55.759 --> 00:01:00.639
At the time, it was about eight years ago, I was a PhD candidate in conservation science

00:01:00.639 --> 00:01:04.959
and I was juggling a collaboration between the government, the university and the department

00:01:04.959 --> 00:01:11.279
of e-research. One day I needed a data set from my government collaborators but this data set was too

00:01:11.279 --> 00:01:17.919
big, too inconsistent, too messy and also too sensitive to be shared online. So one of my

00:01:17.919 --> 00:01:23.360
colleagues copied it into a USB stick, they put it in an envelope and mailed it to me. About three

00:01:23.360 --> 00:01:28.400
weeks later, it arrived in the post. I was able to access the data but then had to deliver that

00:01:28.400 --> 00:01:35.040
same USB stick to the department of e-research. When I delivered it, we had a good laugh. Here we

00:01:35.040 --> 00:01:40.800
were in the 21st century solving some biodiversity problems using snail mail. But it was also a

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:46.000
light bulb moment for me. That little USB stick ended up being a really big turning point.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:50.879
It landed me a new role piloting a platform across all states and territories in Australia

00:01:50.959 --> 00:01:55.519
and that work eventually led to a five million dollar investment from the Australian Research

00:01:55.519 --> 00:02:01.680
Data Commons and the Australian government to what's now EcoCommons. So when I say EcoCommons

00:02:01.680 --> 00:02:07.040
is about accessibility, it's not just theory, it comes from lived experience, from starting my

00:02:07.040 --> 00:02:14.080
career as a human courier service for biodiversity data. That USB moment really showed me just how

00:02:14.080 --> 00:02:19.520
many barriers are in the way. We have messy data, clunky sharing and so much wasted effort.

00:02:20.160 --> 00:02:24.399
So the question then became, what if we could build something better? What if there was one

00:02:24.399 --> 00:02:29.360
place where data, tools and compute power could all come together and anyone could use it? And

00:02:29.360 --> 00:02:35.199
that's what EcoCommons is. EcoCommons is a free, open source, cloud-based platform to remove

00:02:35.199 --> 00:02:40.720
barriers to ecological modelling. It's built using Python with all our models and algorithms developed

00:02:40.720 --> 00:02:45.919
on R packages. It brings together trusted biodiversity and environmental data sets,

00:02:46.399 --> 00:02:50.880
integrates tools for analysis and modelling and makes them available in two key ways.

00:02:51.679 --> 00:02:58.559
Firstly as point and click workflows for people who aren't coders and also as R and Python notebooks

00:02:58.559 --> 00:03:04.000
for those who really love the code. This means a student, a government scientist,

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:10.479
a conservation NGO can all access the same data sets, the same models and get reproducible results.

00:03:11.039 --> 00:03:13.119
This really helps to level the playing field.

00:03:15.360 --> 00:03:20.000
So let's walk through some of the key features. First, EcoCommons brings together thousands of

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:25.119
data sets in one place and they're not just the raw files, they've been curated and standardised

00:03:25.119 --> 00:03:32.000
so they're ready to use, which alone saves weeks of work. Secondly, we make data wrangling easier.

00:03:32.639 --> 00:03:37.199
We've built tools to harmonise formats, manage metadata so you don't have to spend your time

00:03:37.199 --> 00:03:42.960
cleaning data. Thirdly, we've embedded trusted models and algorithms and these are the ones that

00:03:42.960 --> 00:03:49.199
are really widely used and validated by the scientific community. For our advanced users,

00:03:49.199 --> 00:03:53.839
we provide Jupyter notebooks so you can customise workflows or run experiments at scale.

00:03:54.399 --> 00:03:57.919
And all of this runs in the cloud so you're not just using your own machine.

00:03:58.559 --> 00:04:04.399
I've seen many a laptop start to crash just by running one species distribution model and in

00:04:04.399 --> 00:04:11.279
EcoCommons, we can run millions. So finally, everything follows fair data principles. Our

00:04:11.279 --> 00:04:17.279
data and workflows are findable, accessible, interoperable and reusable and this ensures

00:04:17.279 --> 00:04:24.720
that results are high quality, transparent and shareable. Okay, so here's a light-hearted example

00:04:24.720 --> 00:04:30.160
to showcase the platform. We asked the question, if koalas lived in the United States, would they

00:04:30.160 --> 00:04:37.040
prefer the east or the west coast? And let's showcase this using a demonstration. Let's dive

00:04:37.040 --> 00:04:42.399
in with a demonstration. This here is the EcoCommons platform where you can access data sets,

00:04:42.399 --> 00:04:49.040
view your results and run new analyses. We're going to run our species distribution models using the

00:04:49.040 --> 00:04:54.959
Biodiversity and Climate Change Virtual Laboratory. This is where you can conduct species distribution

00:04:54.959 --> 00:05:00.720
models and climate change projections. We're going to use a posit koala example here today.

00:05:02.079 --> 00:05:07.839
The next step is to select your species occurrence records. These are simply records where we know

00:05:07.839 --> 00:05:15.119
koalas already live here in Australia. And we have access to different biodiversity data repositories

00:05:15.119 --> 00:05:19.600
through APIs so a user can simply search the species and then visualise here on the map.

00:05:20.160 --> 00:05:28.000
The next step is to select absence data. Absence data simply is where we know the koalas don't occur

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:33.600
and we run this in the back end of the system using different methods depending on user needs

00:05:33.600 --> 00:05:36.160
and this really just helps improve the model.

00:05:41.519 --> 00:05:47.440
The next step is to select the climate and environmental data. EcoCommons has access to

00:05:47.519 --> 00:05:51.040
EcoCommons has access to thousands of data sets all in one place

00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:54.720
and today we're going to use a global climate data set.

00:05:56.480 --> 00:06:00.799
Here we select the different layers within the data set that we want to use in our model

00:06:00.799 --> 00:06:03.760
and we're selecting a few that we know are important for koalas.

00:06:05.200 --> 00:06:08.239
You can visualise this here on the map. We can see Australia

00:06:08.239 --> 00:06:10.880
and we can zoom out to see what it looks like across the globe.

00:06:11.679 --> 00:06:16.799
The next step is to select the study extent. We're going to use a global extent for this model today.

00:06:18.799 --> 00:06:23.839
Next we want to select our algorithms. We have access to around 20 different algorithms that

00:06:23.839 --> 00:06:30.559
are all built on R packages. A user has the option to change all of the settings they need

00:06:31.119 --> 00:06:33.760
as if they were actually running the R package themselves.

00:06:34.160 --> 00:06:38.640
The next step we hit start experiment. We go grab a coffee and wait for our results.

00:06:39.760 --> 00:06:44.320
Now we can see our job submitted and then we can view our results here.

00:06:45.040 --> 00:06:50.399
So let's see what it looks like for koalas in Australia. We can see a really nice distribution.

00:06:51.040 --> 00:06:54.000
The darker the colour, which in this case is the orange,

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:57.119
is the more likely the species has habitat in that area.

00:06:57.440 --> 00:07:00.480
The darker the colour, which in this case is the orange,

00:07:00.480 --> 00:07:03.600
is the more likely the species has habitat in that area.

00:07:04.480 --> 00:07:10.399
So let's see what it looks like for the States. If we zoom out, we can see that there are some

00:07:10.399 --> 00:07:15.040
really interesting results here for the United States. Let's dive in a little deeper.

00:07:16.640 --> 00:07:21.760
And here are the results. The model suggests that if eucalyptus trees and the appropriate

00:07:21.839 --> 00:07:27.200
habitat was available, koalas could potentially thrive in some interesting places in the United

00:07:27.200 --> 00:07:34.720
States. We can see distribution around Seattle. We can see distribution near Austin in Texas

00:07:34.720 --> 00:07:38.160
and across the Southeast, particularly Georgia and Florida.

00:07:39.440 --> 00:07:43.839
Of course, we're not seriously considering exporting koalas to the US. So while it's really

00:07:43.839 --> 00:07:49.040
fun to see where koalas might like to live in the United States, this example demonstrates

00:07:49.040 --> 00:07:54.559
something much bigger. The ability to ask complex ecological questions and get clear,

00:07:54.559 --> 00:07:59.040
reproducible answers. And that's really important because in the real world,

00:07:59.040 --> 00:08:04.000
we're facing urgent biodiversity challenges, and those same tools are being used to guide

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:08.000
conservation, land management, biodiversity, and climate planning.

00:08:08.559 --> 00:08:11.839
Which brings me to my next point, why this work really matters.

00:08:12.079 --> 00:08:17.200
Globally, biodiversity is unfortunately declining at a pace that we've never seen before.

00:08:17.839 --> 00:08:22.079
Here in Australia, we have one of the highest rates of mammal extinction in the world.

00:08:22.079 --> 00:08:28.000
We have climate change and we have invasive species and habitat loss reshaping ecosystems

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:33.919
faster than we can keep up. To respond effectively, we need trusted models and data.

00:08:33.919 --> 00:08:38.320
We need to know where species are now, how they're likely to shift in the future,

00:08:38.320 --> 00:08:40.960
and what management actions will make the biggest difference.

00:08:42.559 --> 00:08:47.760
And that's the role that EcoCommons plays, turning complex data into the evidence and

00:08:47.760 --> 00:08:53.280
data-driven decisions that we need. But getting to this point really wasn't that simple.

00:08:53.280 --> 00:08:58.320
Before EcoCommons, the barriers made this kind of modelling almost impossible.

00:09:01.520 --> 00:09:05.919
Data was scattered across institutions and often in inconsistent formats.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:08.880
Sometimes only accessible if you knew the right person.

00:09:09.679 --> 00:09:14.479
Running models required high-performance compute, and many ecologists simply don't have access to

00:09:14.479 --> 00:09:20.960
that, so work becomes stalled. Even if you had compute, you needed to have advanced coding skills,

00:09:20.960 --> 00:09:24.799
which can exclude some really brilliant practitioners who just hadn't been trained in

00:09:24.799 --> 00:09:31.280
programming. And on top of that, you need modelling expertise. And even then, the workflows are often

00:09:31.679 --> 00:09:35.760
black boxes. Two people could run what looked to be the same model and end up with really

00:09:35.760 --> 00:09:42.159
different results. So all of this meant that biodiversity modelling could be slow, fragmented,

00:09:42.159 --> 00:09:48.880
and often inaccessible. EcoCommons solves this first barrier with accessible data.

00:09:48.880 --> 00:09:53.599
We integrate trusted biodiversity data and environmental data sets into the platform.

00:09:54.159 --> 00:09:59.039
They're standardised and curated, so they're ready to use. No more USBs,

00:09:59.280 --> 00:10:04.799
no more hunting down files across multiple institutions. This makes modelling faster,

00:10:04.799 --> 00:10:09.440
but also makes it fairer. Everyone works from the same reliable data foundation.

00:10:10.880 --> 00:10:15.359
EcoCommons runs in the cloud, so a lot of that heavy lifting happens behind the scenes.

00:10:15.359 --> 00:10:20.400
You don't need to own or rent a supercomputer. Whether you're running a small student project

00:10:20.400 --> 00:10:25.280
with a few models, or a government project running millions of models, the platform scales to fit.

00:10:25.280 --> 00:10:29.679
This opens the doors for non-government organisations, non-for-profits,

00:10:29.679 --> 00:10:33.679
smaller research groups, and anyone who doesn't have expensive infrastructure.

00:10:35.679 --> 00:10:40.080
And skills are another big barrier. EcoCommons provides point-and-click workflows for people

00:10:40.080 --> 00:10:45.280
new to modelling. They can select data sets, choose algorithms, and run analyses through

00:10:45.280 --> 00:10:50.880
an intuitive interface. At the same time, our coders can integrate R and Python directly,

00:10:51.039 --> 00:10:54.719
At the same time, our coders can integrate R and Python directly,

00:10:54.719 --> 00:10:59.039
so they're not limited by the interface. And we do this through the Jupyter Notebook library.

00:11:00.479 --> 00:11:04.479
We also run a lot of training and provide documentation, helping people build their

00:11:04.479 --> 00:11:10.320
confidence and skills over time. And the result here is instead of locking people out of modelling,

00:11:10.320 --> 00:11:16.799
we're really helping to bring them in. And finally, methods. Too often, ecological modelling,

00:11:16.880 --> 00:11:21.760
or modelling as a whole, has been inconsistent or opaque. You don't always know what steps have

00:11:21.760 --> 00:11:26.880
been taken, and you can't always reproduce someone else's results. So, we've made these

00:11:26.880 --> 00:11:32.559
workflows open, transparent, and reproducible. Every step is documented, and the methods can

00:11:32.559 --> 00:11:38.799
be shared and modifiable. This transparency builds trust and also helps accelerate science,

00:11:38.799 --> 00:11:41.840
because the results can be repeated, compared, and improved.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:47.599
So, what does all this add up to? EcoCommons is helping conservation groups plan on-ground actions,

00:11:47.599 --> 00:11:52.719
it's helping governments assess risk and make policy decisions, it's supporting NGOs and

00:11:52.719 --> 00:11:58.320
researchers who want to test new ideas and scale up models. And beyond individual projects,

00:11:58.320 --> 00:12:03.200
it's building a community of practice. People aren't just using EcoCommons in isolation,

00:12:03.200 --> 00:12:07.359
they're sharing their workflows, contributing data sets, and really learning from one another.

00:12:07.520 --> 00:12:12.880
So, I want to ground this impact into a real story, and let's use the northern eastern bristlebird

00:12:12.880 --> 00:12:18.640
as an example. This bird has less than 40 individuals left in the wild here in Australia,

00:12:18.640 --> 00:12:24.559
and they hide in really dense patches across our southeast Queensland and northeast New South Wales.

00:12:25.440 --> 00:12:31.359
EcoCommons is helping to model the habitat with BirdLife Australia, to highlight likely sites for

00:12:31.440 --> 00:12:37.440
This has helped their field teams to focus surveys and deploy eco-acoustic recorders efficiently,

00:12:37.440 --> 00:12:43.440
saving time and resources. And already, it's really exciting results. We have new promising sites,

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:49.200
and we are directly informing monitoring and recovery strategies, showing that what EcoCommons

00:12:49.200 --> 00:12:55.359
is really about, practical and targeted impact for the birds. So, this is a really exciting

00:12:55.760 --> 00:13:01.119
strategies, showing that what EcoCommons is really about, practical and targeted impact

00:13:01.119 --> 00:13:08.000
for conservation. We've really learned a lot in building EcoCommons. Scaling our workflows

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:13.200
to run millions of models was definitely technically challenging. We had to rethink

00:13:13.200 --> 00:13:19.200
our performance, our reproducibility, and how to handle large data sets. And we're consistently

00:13:19.200 --> 00:13:24.320
improving on this as well. We've had to balance the needs of really different user groups,

00:13:24.320 --> 00:13:29.599
so we've had advanced coders who want to have full flexibility, and newcomers to the industry

00:13:29.599 --> 00:13:34.559
who just want something intuitive. And we've really learned the importance of community feedback.

00:13:35.119 --> 00:13:39.599
Many of our improvements come directly from what users are telling us what worked,

00:13:39.599 --> 00:13:46.559
what didn't, and what they needed next. And EcoCommons really isn't just a platform,

00:13:46.559 --> 00:13:51.760
it's a community of practice. We're building this together with researchers, government agencies,

00:13:51.760 --> 00:13:57.520
NGOs, and students, which means sharing tools, workflows, and providing training and support,

00:13:57.520 --> 00:14:02.640
and really learning from each other's experiences. The strength of a platform like this comes not

00:14:02.640 --> 00:14:07.440
only from the technology, which is great, but really what's important is the people.

00:14:08.880 --> 00:14:14.239
This community approach is what makes our platform sustainable and impactful in the long term.

00:14:16.080 --> 00:14:21.520
So, let's come back to that USB in the post. We've come a really long way since mailing data around.

00:14:22.080 --> 00:14:27.520
And EcoCommons is about breaking down these barriers, so data, tools, and conservation

00:14:27.520 --> 00:14:33.200
impact are accessible to everyone. I'd really like to invite you to try it out, contribute data sets

00:14:33.200 --> 00:14:38.640
or workflows, and join our community. Because when accessibility is built in from the beginning,

00:14:38.640 --> 00:14:42.000
we can move faster, and we can do better science for the planet.

00:14:44.239 --> 00:14:48.559
If you're interested in learning a bit more about EcoCommons, please check out one of our papers

00:14:48.559 --> 00:14:52.960
that explains our methods, and also has some really nice case studies that you can look at.

